@guotong1988 
Honestly, I am not familiar with that part. To the best of my knowledge, this job is done by client or AppMaster. You can find more information in `tracker.py` and `ApplicationMaster.java`.

By the way, you should set more memory for containers (2-4GB), otherwise they will run out of memory.

@sxjscience Sorry, I didn't make it clear. When I said **"so the policy output should be SoftmaxActivation(with advantage as out_gradient) instead of SoftmaxOutput."**, I actually meant log(SoftmaxActivation), you can refer [here](https://github.com/loofahcus/mxnet/blob/parallel_actor_critic/example/reinforcement-learning/parallel_actor_critic/model.py#L27), that's why I said SoftmaxOutput is not proper.

I myself didn't try other games like BreakOut, but I refered to other A3C implementation like [async-rl](https://github.com/muupan/async-rl) and quit sure the implementation is right. The [shared net](https://github.com/loofahcus/mxnet/blob/parallel_actor_critic/example/reinforcement-learning/parallel_actor_critic/model.py#L18) uses MLP instead of CNN, since [Atari8080Preprocessor](https://github.com/loofahcus/mxnet/blob/parallel_actor_critic/example/reinforcement-learning/parallel_actor_critic/envs.py#L4) simplifies the observation into “binary image”, which leads to fast learning, and so it may not fit other games. Since this implementation focuses on right implementation of network structure for actor-critic, it's not a big deal.

By the way, in my opinion, the biggest difference between **A3C** and **Parallel Actor Critic** may lie in the rate of convergence, A3C may benefit from its hogwild learning schema.

